40 tekster i Khen ze chin van samlingen, nr. 8. Khen ze chin van alias Prins Yunli (Kengse qinwang) (1697-1738) har sat sit segl i nogle af titelbladene i samlingen, så de foreliggende håndskrifter kan således dateres til 1700 tallet.
Denne samling blev erhvervet af danskeren Sophus Black i 1920erne under sit ophold i Beijing for Store Nordiske Telegraf-Selskab.
Titlerne er beskrevet i: Catalogue of Tibetan Manuscripts af Hartmut Buescher og Tarab Tulku, Copenhagen: Det Kongelige Bibliotek, Curzon, 2000, se side 910-911, og s. 1036.
Prins Yunli er beskrevet i: Prince Yunli (1697-1738) - Manchu Statesman and Tibetan Buddhist af Vladimir L. Uspensky. Tokyo: Institute for the study of languages and cultures of Asia and Africa, 1997.
Bl. 8

The texts are a part of the Khen ze chin van collection, no. 8. Khen ze chin van alias Prince Yun-li (Kengse qinwang) (1697-1738 CE) have added his personal stamp on some of the title pages in the collection, e.g. the manuskript can be dated to the early part of 18th Century.
This collection was acquired by the Dane Sophus Black in 1920's during his stay in Beijing for The Great Nordic Telegraph-Company.
The titles have been described in: Catalogue of Tibetan Manuscripts by Hartmut Buescher and Tarab Tulku, Copenhagen: Det Kongelige Bibliotek, Curzon, 2000, see pp. 910-911, and p. 1036.
Prins Yunli is described in: Prince Yunli (1697-1738) - Manchu Statesman and Tibetan Buddhist by Vladimir L. Uspensky. Tokyo: Institute for the study of languages and cultures of Asia and Africa, 1997.
BL. 8
